ic poetry; the authenticity of writing and the distortions of speech in scientific prose works; the social context of printing scientific prose; and the use of print to create the infinitely expandable text of philosophical skepticism.A provocative application of contemporary literary theory to the historical analysis of texts, Authorizing Words will interest readers in such disciplines as Renaissance studies, theory of language, historical linguistics, history of science, and the history of communication.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Sep 2019) 0aEnglish languageyEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aHumanistszEngland. 0aLanguage and languagesxPhilosophyxHistoryy17th century. 0aOral communicationzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aPrintingzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aRenaissance. 0aWritten communicationzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501745744423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501745744.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG